  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Hurricane Hugo did not simply wreak devastation on the Carolinas;
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   it brought about repayment of a long overdue debt.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Kingston, N.Y., the capital of New York in 1777, was burned by the British in October of that year.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   New York Gov. George Clinton received from South Carolina Gov. Abraham Livingston a letter dated March 31, 1778 enclosing 1,000 New York pounds "...for the charitable purpose of alleviating the distresses of the now-indigent inhabitants of the town of Kingston...".
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   A local historian remembered the letter
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   and now Kingston is raising money to help Charleston, S.C. recover from the ravages of Hugo.
  </a>
